00:21:46.440 --> 00:21:49.120
uv, maybe a quick summary for what it is.

00:21:49.300 --> 00:21:50.800
And then we could talk about your post,

00:21:51.540 --> 00:21:55.560
which adds layers of features and capabilities as we start.

00:21:55.560 --> 00:21:56.060
Yeah, totally.

00:21:57.800 --> 00:22:00.600
So I came on the show back in March

00:22:00.650 --> 00:22:03.340
and we talked a bit about what uv was at the time.

00:22:03.750 --> 00:22:05.380
We released uv in like mid-February.

00:22:05.470 --> 00:22:06.600
So that was a couple of weeks after.

00:22:08.580 --> 00:22:11.240
And uv is our Python packaging tool.

00:22:12.320 --> 00:22:21.800
And it's built under a lot of the same design goals as we had for Ruff.

00:22:22.040 --> 00:22:24.920
So we wanted it to be extremely fast.

00:22:26.060 --> 00:22:29.080
We wanted it to try and bundle a few more things together

00:22:29.300 --> 00:22:33.100
so that you could use fewer tools to work with Python and be productive with Python.

00:22:34.360 --> 00:22:36.660
And we wanted it to be really easy to adopt.

00:22:37.020 --> 00:22:38.760
That was another principle that we thought about a lot.

00:22:38.980 --> 00:22:46.580
So when we released uv in February, it was framed as a pip alternative.

00:22:47.380 --> 00:22:53.300
So the idea was if you use pip before, you know, pip install, pip uninstall, or tools

00:22:53.460 --> 00:22:57.800
like pip compile or pip sync, it should be really familiar to you.

00:22:57.800 --> 00:23:03.560
So the API that we started with was like uv pip install, uv pip uninstall, uv pip compile.

00:23:04.320 --> 00:23:06.580
And it was meant to kind of mirror the pip API.

00:23:07.280 --> 00:23:14.300
And the idea there was we wanted it to hopefully be immediately obvious to people like how this tool works and what it does.

00:23:14.600 --> 00:23:16.520
And also, I guess, to some degree, what it doesn't do.

00:23:18.420 --> 00:23:22.960
So we released that in February and it grew extremely fast.

00:23:25.200 --> 00:23:32.740
It's yeah, it's just the adoption, both in terms of like raw numbers and just like the companies that we talk to that are using it like very quickly.

00:23:32.780 --> 00:23:37.440
a lot of people were using it. I consider it a big success. I'm really happy with how that went.

00:23:38.200 --> 00:23:44.320
But it was also, I think, a pretty small portion of what we wanted to build for packaging.

00:23:46.100 --> 00:23:52.400
Ultimately, we weren't trying to build just a faster pip. I think it's a really good starting

00:23:52.560 --> 00:24:00.860
point for a couple of reasons. One, much easier for people to adopt. Two, it required us to build

00:24:00.880 --> 00:24:06.080
a lot of the fundamental pieces that you need for Python packaging. In order to build a PIP

00:24:06.180 --> 00:24:11.420
alternative, we had to be able to resolve Python dependencies, install Python packages,

00:24:12.460 --> 00:24:16.320
understand virtual environments, manipulate all those things. We had to implement a bunch of

00:24:16.520 --> 00:24:22.560
standards around introspecting built distributions and source distributions in virtual environments.

00:24:22.820 --> 00:24:28.960
So we had to invest in all these things that I view as fundamental primitives of working with

00:24:28.800 --> 00:24:29.500
with Python packaging.

00:24:30.420 --> 00:24:32.580
But the ultimate goal for us was always

00:24:33.100 --> 00:24:34.900
we want to build something that's

00:24:35.840 --> 00:24:38.240
like a single static binary that you download and install

00:24:38.380 --> 00:24:40.020
that just gives you everything you need

00:24:40.020 --> 00:24:40.960
to be productive with Python.

00:24:41.980 --> 00:24:44.140
And from that perspective, a pip alternative is

00:24:44.400 --> 00:24:45.320
it's pretty low level.

00:24:46.360 --> 00:24:47.860
And we wanted to build something that was a little bit more

00:24:48.060 --> 00:24:51.340
high level, something that can install Python for you,

00:24:51.520 --> 00:24:54.260
something that can manage the virtual environment for you,

00:24:54.400 --> 00:24:57.100
something where you just do run this file

00:24:57.120 --> 00:25:01.300
it figures out the dependencies installs them it creates the environments and it runs this violin

00:25:01.460 --> 00:25:05.920
the environment like that is what we wanted to build so that's what we've been building up to

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:13.340
over the past couple of months yeah amazing of course you've got to have the uv pip features

00:25:14.200 --> 00:25:19.820
as a foundation right because right even if you don't kind of like we talked earlier even if you

00:25:19.840 --> 00:25:28.700
don't expose it directly as a CLI thing that from a project management perspective, it's needed,

00:25:28.780 --> 00:25:36.520
right? Yeah. And like, it's part of kind of like meeting people where they are to a certain degree.

00:25:37.280 --> 00:25:41.560
Like everyone has workflows that are built around pip. Like even people that do other package that

00:25:41.640 --> 00:25:45.820
have other packaging workflows, often those workflows are actually built around pip commands.

00:25:46.620 --> 00:26:16.420
And like I said, I view those as a little bit low level, like with pip, the operations are kind of like, install this package into this environment, as opposed to here, my dependencies, make sure the world is like in sync with my dependencies. That's what I would consider to be like a little bit more high level. So, you know, we built and released that pip interface in February. And since then, we've, you know, it's basically been like hammered right by by users. So it's just gotten like better and better, because they find problems with it, and then report them. And it just gets, you know, it gets better, it gets faster.

00:26:16.620 --> 00:26:20.880
it's like more feature complete so we've had a few months to kind of improve and build on top of it

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:27.820
too yeah that's one of the benefits of such it taking taking hold so much and people using it

00:26:27.940 --> 00:26:32.880
so much as they hit the little edge cases all the time and yeah a lot of edge cases

00:26:34.020 --> 00:26:41.799
yeah i bet i bet yeah um yeah but it's it's yeah it's super fun like set of problems to work on

00:26:41.820 --> 00:26:50.120
by the way, and like really different from rough too. Like, yeah, rough is rough is more like,

00:26:50.370 --> 00:26:56.220
uh, it's more like a compiler. I would say like, we have like a parser and Alexa, you know,

00:26:56.400 --> 00:27:02.300
all that kind of stuff. And with uv, it's a lot more, how do we do IO really fast? Like we have

00:27:02.320 --> 00:27:06.460
a lot of networking. We're like reading and writing from disc a lot. there's a lot of interfacing

00:27:06.480 --> 00:27:13.520
with standards, a lot of interfacing with the registry, everything's async. So it's just like

00:27:13.520 --> 00:27:17.680
a very different set of problems. And it's fun to get to kind of work on both of them because

00:27:18.080 --> 00:27:22.120
they're just really different. Yeah, I'm sure they're both phone projects. And there's some

00:27:22.200 --> 00:27:30.779
really good ideas and questions in the audience, but we're not ready for them. So I think when we

00:27:30.800 --> 00:27:40.800
spoke back in march one of the things we discussed is how you structured the cli api in a way to leave

00:27:41.100 --> 00:27:48.960
space so for example it's not uv install package it's uv pip install package and it's not yes uv

00:27:49.380 --> 00:27:55.660
compile --update for dependence it's uv pip compile or whatever the command is right i have

00:27:55.680 --> 00:28:00.220
it alias to a couple of letters and i never think about it again but something you know that's

00:28:00.900 --> 00:28:07.280
you've left space in the CLI with these sub commands. And I think now we're starting to see

00:28:07.940 --> 00:28:12.580
why you left space. Is that right? Yeah. Yeah. That was like pretty controversial at the time

00:28:12.650 --> 00:28:18.980
and users really hated it. I mean, they still used it, but like it's so much better. I'll use it.

00:28:18.990 --> 00:28:24.220
A lot of people complained about it. I even found it, you know, I even found myself saying like,

00:28:24.380 --> 00:28:28.840
maybe we should, maybe we should stop doing this. Like maybe we should just give up because like

00:28:28.820 --> 00:28:35.000
people were complaining and I was annoyed by it and stuff. But yeah, it's either a huge,

00:28:35.370 --> 00:28:41.240
obviously, it's either a terrible mistake or it was genius. I don't actually know. But what it did

00:28:41.420 --> 00:28:46.620
was, one effect, which I said before, was it immediately conveyed the rough shape of the

00:28:46.820 --> 00:28:51.160
commands like uv pip install. And then if you've used pip install, you know that the next argument

00:28:51.300 --> 00:28:57.280
is a package name or a requirements file. But the other thing it did is it left space in the CLI

00:28:57.300 --> 00:29:01.880
for these new APIs that are sort of first-class uv APIs.

00:29:02.580 --> 00:29:05.000
So instead of doing uv install,

00:29:05.740 --> 00:29:07.300
when we released in February, it was uv pip install,

00:29:08.100 --> 00:29:10.060
which meant that today, this new set of APIs

00:29:10.400 --> 00:29:14.340
that we launched, let's see, two weeks ago, I think today.

00:29:14.960 --> 00:29:15.920
Scroll up, is there a date?

00:29:15.920 --> 00:29:16.880
They're August 20th.

00:29:18.880 --> 00:29:21.560
So this new set of APIs that we released

00:29:21.760 --> 00:29:25.100
are uv lock, uv sync, uv run.

00:29:25.280 --> 00:29:26.540
They can all be top level

00:29:26.560 --> 00:29:29.060
because they're really like the first class uv workflows.

00:29:30.700 --> 00:29:34.320
The pip API, by the way, still 100% there.

00:29:34.450 --> 00:29:36.740
And like, we're going to invest in it a lot

00:29:36.920 --> 00:29:38.080
and like continue maintaining it.

00:29:38.080 --> 00:29:40.740
Cause like that is how most people use uv.

00:29:41.680 --> 00:29:43.900
And maybe eventually we want that to be less true, right?

00:29:43.940 --> 00:29:44.540
Like, right.

00:29:44.550 --> 00:29:46.380
Like we hope more and more people use the new stuff.

00:29:47.050 --> 00:29:48.540
But like, we're going to keep building that.

00:29:49.260 --> 00:29:50.600
But for projects that can,

00:29:50.670 --> 00:29:54.500
we now have this new interface that if you can fit into it,

00:29:54.800 --> 00:29:56.900
it's just sort of more powerful and does more for you.

00:29:57.300 --> 00:30:00.740
So we saved space in the CLI exactly for this reason,

00:30:01.200 --> 00:30:03.520
which is we had a bunch of stuff we knew we wanted to build.

00:30:03.960 --> 00:30:06.720
And if we polluted, well, not polluted, it's the wrong word,

00:30:07.020 --> 00:30:10.020
but if we polluted the interface with uv install,

00:30:10.480 --> 00:30:11.760
if you clogged it.

00:30:12.360 --> 00:30:15.560
Yeah, if we lost all that space to those existing commands,

00:30:15.560 --> 00:30:16.220
it would make things harder.

00:30:16.780 --> 00:30:18.100
So I think it's worked.

00:30:18.740 --> 00:30:19.040
It's done.

00:30:19.360 --> 00:30:20.980
It's had the intended effect for us.

00:30:22.280 --> 00:30:23.560
It kept the space open.

00:30:23.840 --> 00:30:24.760
It let people use it.

00:30:24.780 --> 00:30:25.880
It conveyed how it works.

00:30:27.340 --> 00:30:29.060
And now they kind of exist alongside each other.

00:30:29.140 --> 00:30:32.340
And the pip API, you can kind of use them together in certain ways.

00:30:32.440 --> 00:30:36.220
And when you use them together, you sort of realize that the pip API is more low level.

00:30:36.680 --> 00:30:42.820
It's like the new APIs, you have a pi project toml file with your requirements in it, and you just run uv sync.

00:30:43.080 --> 00:30:46.560
And it will resolve them, create a lock file, install them in a virtual environment.

00:30:46.840 --> 00:30:47.520
That's like one command.

00:30:48.720 --> 00:30:50.760
You could then modify the virtual environment.

00:30:51.100 --> 00:30:53.140
You could do UVPIP install, blah, blah, blah,

00:30:53.270 --> 00:30:54.980
and start making edits to it.

00:30:55.520 --> 00:30:56.860
That illustrates what I mean by

00:30:57.430 --> 00:30:58.720
it's a low-level pip APIs

00:30:58.950 --> 00:31:00.560
where you're manually manipulating things

00:31:00.710 --> 00:31:01.860
versus these higher-level APIs

00:31:02.050 --> 00:31:04.620
where you tell us what your dependencies are

00:31:04.730 --> 00:31:06.240
and then we figure everything out for you.

00:31:07.580 --> 00:31:08.400
Yeah, that's excellent.

